1
00:00:02,225 --> 00:00:27,388
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhodassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhodassa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambhodassa

2
00:00:27,942 --> 00:00:34,509
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

3
00:00:34,649 --> 00:00:42,939
So last week I did what is arguably the most famous of the verses in the Dhammapada.

4
00:00:43,560 --> 00:00:50,328
This week I want to go back to the very beginning of it and it opens up with twin verses.

5
00:00:50,688 --> 00:00:54,792
So one verse says positive and the other verse says the negative.

6
00:00:55,381 --> 00:00:59,886
And the first two really are core teachings of the Buddha.

7
00:00:59,905 --> 00:01:07,275
So I'd like to chant it first in Pali, and then a simple translation, and then we'll read the story.

8
00:01:09,596 --> 00:01:20,409
Mano Pubhanga Madhamma Mano Seta Mano Maya Manasa Chapa Dutena Vasati Wa Karoti Wa

9
00:01:20,879 --> 00:01:26,865
tatonandukkhamamvaiti chakamvavahato padam.

10
00:01:27,706 --> 00:01:28,387
And the opposite.

11
00:01:29,368 --> 00:01:47,629
Manopubangamadamma manoseitamanomaya manasacchapasaneinavasatiwakarotiwa tatonandsukkhamamvaiti chayavaanapayini.

12
00:01:50,748 --> 00:02:19,421
need i translate so a very uh a sort of literal translation the most literal that i've come across was by buddha rakita mind proceeds all mental states mind is their chief they are all mine wrought if with an impure mind a person speaks or acts suffering follows him like the wheel that follows the foot of an ox

13
00:02:20,312 --> 00:02:48,042
mind proceeds all mental states mind is their chief mind are all mind they are all mind wrought if with a pure mind a person speaks or acts happiness follows him like his never departing shadow so if we read the little story that uh that's always with these verses so it's the anahat who lost his eyesight

14
00:02:48,949 --> 00:02:57,259
One day, Venerable Chakrapala, who was blind, came to pay homage to the Buddha at the Jetavana monastery.

15
00:02:58,100 --> 00:03:03,706
While he was pacing up and down in meditation, he accidentally stepped on some insects.

16
00:03:04,788 --> 00:03:08,612
In the morning, some bhikkhus visiting him found the dead insects.

17
00:03:09,252 --> 00:03:12,477
They thought ill of him and reported the matter to the Buddha.

18
00:03:13,806 --> 00:03:23,578
When questioned by the Buddha whether they had actually seen Chakrapala killing the insects, they answered in the negative, and the Buddha then admonished them.

19
00:03:24,438 --> 00:03:30,664
Just as you had not seen him killing, so also you had not seen those living insects.

20
00:03:31,605 --> 00:03:39,594
Besides, being an Arahant, he had no intention of killing and was not guilty of committing an unwholesome act.

21
00:03:40,856 --> 00:03:48,911
On being asked why Chakrapala was blind, the Buddha revealed the following story to explain the nature of karmic effects.

22
00:03:50,193 --> 00:03:54,118
Chakrapala had been a physician in one of his past existences.

23
00:03:55,100 --> 00:03:58,826
Once he had deliberately made a woman patient blind.

24
00:03:59,729 --> 00:04:07,100
That woman had promised to become his servant together with her children if her eyes were completely cured.

25
00:04:08,161 --> 00:04:13,866
Fearing that she and her children would have to become servants, she lied to the physician.

26
00:04:14,486 --> 00:04:19,612
She told him that her eyes were getting worse when in fact they were perfectly cured.

27
00:04:19,653 --> 00:04:28,622
The physician knew she was deceiving him, so in revenge he gave her another ointment which made her totally blind.

28
00:04:29,642 --> 00:04:36,430
As a result of this evil deed, the physician lost his eyesight many times in later existences.

29
00:04:37,338 --> 00:04:46,709
The Buddha then commented that an evil deed committed will follow the evildoer, just like the wheel follows the hoof of an ox that bears the yoke.

30
00:04:47,910 --> 00:05:03,528
So I dare say there's a core truth to the story somewhere about an Arhat killing insects and being thought guilty of doing it on purpose.

31
00:05:04,709 --> 00:05:07,091
But of course, his name, Chakupala,

32
00:05:07,476 --> 00:05:10,661
ironically means guardian of eyesight.

33
00:05:11,101 --> 00:05:14,447
So I doubt a monk is called guardian of eyesight.

34
00:05:15,649 --> 00:05:18,973
Anyway, there's two points here.

35
00:05:19,074 --> 00:05:29,290
First of all, is that he's not guilty because he doesn't mean, he hadn't meant to kill, right?

36
00:05:29,350 --> 00:05:30,891
That's the important thing.

37
00:05:30,911 --> 00:05:36,740
And that because he in a past life had committed this terrible deed of making somebody blind,

38
00:05:36,939 --> 00:05:58,154
himself suffered blindness so that's a very sort of mechanical understanding of karma it's a bit more subtle than that and uh i think at a later time we might go into it but uh let's look at the at the actual pali here so that we can understand what the buddha's uh saying uh mano

39
00:06:00,007 --> 00:06:10,742
Mano refers to the part of the mind that when you see something, and it's the same for all the senses, you create a percept, like a photocopy.

40
00:06:10,762 --> 00:06:12,826
And as a human being, you put a label on it.

41
00:06:13,065 --> 00:06:15,149
So all animals have memory.

42
00:06:15,730 --> 00:06:18,173
I mean, they remember their owner.

43
00:06:18,454 --> 00:06:20,776
The dog remembers its owner.

44
00:06:21,918 --> 00:06:25,002
But they don't have that facility of putting a label on it.

45
00:06:25,658 --> 00:06:33,367
And so if we think of mano referring to the imagination and intellectual capacity of the mind.

46
00:06:34,408 --> 00:06:41,797
Now, the word for the heart coming from our emotional involvement in life, feeling, that's citta.

47
00:06:42,858 --> 00:06:49,927
And the vijnana refers to consciousness, which is the screen upon which things come to be known.

48
00:06:50,608 --> 00:06:54,331
Now, these words are sometimes used to mean each other.

49
00:06:54,733 --> 00:06:58,697
So you have to look at the context, but generally speaking, that's the split.

50
00:06:59,298 --> 00:07:12,711
Now that isn't so surprising for us because even in our own history, through our wonderful enlightenment, I think the 18th century, we got very rational and we have the great philosopher Kant.

51
00:07:13,452 --> 00:07:23,002
And as opposed to that, as a sort of rejection of pure logic, we have the Romantic movement, which is much more to do with feeling.

52
00:07:23,523 --> 00:07:46,105
so that that dichotomy also exists in in the buddhist psychology and what he says is that this faculty this mind uh it comes before right it instigates it starts things without that without that faculty uh we wouldn't have this imagination and so on

53
00:07:47,940 --> 00:08:12,564
and then this word dharma now we know it normally as meaning the teachings but in its plural form dhamma it means what the mind actually creates so it's mental heart phenomena the actual philosophical word for it is qualia i just like that word so

54
00:08:13,776 --> 00:08:19,586
If you come across the word qualia, it's referring to your subjective conscious experience.

55
00:08:20,668 --> 00:08:23,814
So this is what Dhamma is here referring to.

56
00:08:25,817 --> 00:08:29,283
And then, of course, he says it's Mano Seta.

57
00:08:29,343 --> 00:08:33,549
Seta is the one who governs, who rules.

58
00:08:33,791 --> 00:08:36,375
So it's the mind that's ruling this process.

59
00:08:37,081 --> 00:08:47,712
And finally, Manomaya, which refers to the mind, its ability to fabricate, to make, to produce.

60
00:08:48,774 --> 00:08:52,437
So that's the basic statement.

61
00:08:52,477 --> 00:09:04,692
Now, if we were to take that statement entirely on its own, then you might be thinking that the Buddha is teaching a sort of idealism, that there is only the mind.

62
00:09:05,379 --> 00:09:21,144
which of course does happen in later Buddhism at the Vijnanavada school, Theravada tends to keep a hold on realism in the sense that it doesn't deny the reality, that's inverted commas of course, of the world outside the mind.

63
00:09:21,424 --> 00:09:26,413
So when you look at a tree, the tree actually does exist, have its own existence out there.

64
00:09:27,153 --> 00:09:30,779
But what we actually see of it, of course, is being fabricated.

65
00:09:33,123 --> 00:09:39,494
So, but then when we see, when we read the rest of the verse, he's actually talking about something quite specific.

66
00:09:40,696 --> 00:09:54,220
The next one is, of course, if with an impure mind, a part butena, so with an impure mind, somebody speaks or acts, then suffering will follow them.

67
00:09:54,418 --> 00:09:57,282
So there's your process.

68
00:09:57,381 --> 00:10:07,594
Now, there's an incident in the scriptures where the Buddha meets a disciple of the Jain leader.

69
00:10:08,475 --> 00:10:11,979
And when he asked the Jain leader, what does the Jain leader teach about karma?

70
00:10:11,999 --> 00:10:15,142
He says, the worst thing is an action, is a bad action.

71
00:10:16,243 --> 00:10:24,072
Now, from one point of view, of course, it is because that's the outer consequence of bad thinking and it causes a lot of suffering.

72
00:10:24,777 --> 00:10:31,125
But the Buddha's insistence is that actually what's most important is your mind because that's where it all begins.

73
00:10:32,227 --> 00:10:40,599
And so here we have the mind offering us an unwholesome thought and we empower that.

74
00:10:41,019 --> 00:10:43,442
So there's a bit of empowerment.

75
00:10:43,884 --> 00:10:53,096
And this moment of empowerment, which is chaitanya, that's the faculty of will, is the moment that we're actually creating something.

76
00:10:54,494 --> 00:11:22,830
now once something's in the mind buzzing around in the mind it doesn't take too long for it to be uh you know to begin to express itself in the way we speak and in what we do so the buddha is saying you know be careful about what you think and um that chaitanya that will is the point where you actually make a decision uh to express something either in speech or in action right

77
00:11:23,062 --> 00:11:24,884
And it all begins in the mind.

78
00:11:27,889 --> 00:11:33,895
So then of course he warns us that if we do that, then of course suffering will follow, right?

79
00:11:33,916 --> 00:11:37,460
There'll be some comeback, there'll be some consequence.

80
00:11:37,480 --> 00:11:44,187
And he uses this image, he's got lots of images, he's very good on metaphors.

81
00:11:45,708 --> 00:11:50,774
So it's just like, it'll follow you, it'll chase you down,

82
00:11:51,126 --> 00:11:54,150
just like the wheel follows the footstep of an ox.

83
00:11:54,652 --> 00:12:05,004
So here we have an image of burdensome, you know, a beast of burden, just the life that is burdened.

84
00:12:05,625 --> 00:12:10,131
And so every time we do something which is unwholesome, this burden will arise.

85
00:12:11,413 --> 00:12:16,880
And of course, in the opposite one, he gives a different example.

86
00:12:17,485 --> 00:12:44,336
different image so here of course we're we're thinking wholesome thoughts and we're speaking wholesomely and we're acting wholesomely so then he says of course happiness follows like a never-ending shadow so it's very light something that you don't even notice but it's following you all the time so

87
00:12:45,312 --> 00:12:50,979
The teaching here basically is, you know, just be careful of what we think about.

88
00:12:51,019 --> 00:12:52,760
That's the basic teaching.

89
00:12:53,581 --> 00:12:56,446
And it starts the whole of the Dhammapada.

90
00:12:56,625 --> 00:12:59,870
And then the Dhammapada, of course, goes into all sorts of different subjects.

91
00:13:00,331 --> 00:13:08,421
But later on, there's lots of little verses teaching about karma itself.

92
00:13:09,261 --> 00:13:10,864
And that's a bit too much for this evening.

93
00:13:12,716 --> 00:13:19,184
So that's the two opening verses of the Dhammapada.

94
00:13:19,205 --> 00:13:28,236
And I shall suffer you to hear my own little translation.

95
00:13:31,341 --> 00:13:34,965
All thinking and imagining are started by the mind.

96
00:13:35,826 --> 00:13:37,629
The mind is in charge of them.

97
00:13:37,649 --> 00:13:38,970
The mind fabricates them.

98
00:13:39,831 --> 00:13:42,554
And as we speak or behave with an impure mind,

99
00:13:42,940 --> 00:13:49,087
suffering will follow as a consequence, as the cartwheels follow the hooves of an ox.

100
00:13:49,869 --> 00:13:52,572
So that's my little gift for this evening.

101
00:13:52,613 --> 00:14:05,590
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance and that by your devoted practice you will be liberated from all suffering sooner rather than later.

